      <div class="col-sm-7">
        <h2></h2>
        
            <div class="gen-group">
              
                <div class="gen-group__logo"><img src="https://d1o1wdbk5ytaqh.cloudfront.net/media/hockerton-logo" /></div>
              
              <div class="gen-group__content">
                <p class="subheading">Site managed by</p>
                <h2>Sustainable Hockerton Wind Turbine</h2>
              </div>
            </div>
        
        <div class="gen-content">
          <p>Sustainable Hockerton supports and runs activities for the benefit of the village and to encourage working towards a low-carbon and sustainable future. </p>
<p>Sustainable Hockerton was officially set up in 2010, after four years as an informal working group. There are now 78 members in the society. After looking for solutions to help make the village sustainable, the group decided to invest in a wind turbine because it would be profitable enough to fund additional sustainability projects. The turbine is one of the first community owned wind turbines in the UK, and is a step towards energy security and climate change mitigation, as well as increasing community resilience and cohesion.  </p>
<p>The revenue generated through the Sustainable Hockerton Wind Turbine funds new renewable energy projects and educational tours, and is used to promote energy conservation including Â£200 grants for people to buy energy-efficient items such as insulation and low energy light-bulbs.</p>
<p>While Sustainable Hockerton owns the site, Hockerton Housing Project, a community business and a self-sufficient co-housing development, manages the turbine.</p>
          <p class="read-more"><a href="#" class="button">Read More</a></p>
        </div>
        

